                                     {
                                         "text":  "The Inca Empire (<i>Tawantinsuyu</i>) in the South American subcontinent (<i>Abya Yala</i>) is detailed in the genealogy of Inca kings (<i>Sapa</i>)",
                                         "source":  [
                                                        {
                                                            "type":  1,
                                                            "uuid":  "922ae4e4-8a1a-40ed-9fa3-ca7d541a05e1",
                                                            "text":  "History Tracers Team",
                                                            "page":  "",
                                                            "date_time":  {
                                                                              "type":  "gregory",
                                                                              "year":  "2024",
                                                                              "month":  "",
                                                                              "day":  ""
                                                                          }
                                                        }
                                                    ],
                                         "date_time":  null,
                                         "isTable":  false,
                                         "imgdesc":  "",
                                         "format":  "html",
                                         "PostMention":  "."
                                     },
                                     {
                                         "text":  "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection: External Influences (Part II)</b><br /><br />In analyzing the account given by Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala on Inca rulers, we find an intriguing fragment where he describes Jesus Christ as the son of Mama Coca, wife (<i>Coya</i>) of Sinchi Roca. Interestingly, in another part of the same book, Guaman Poma presents Jesus Christ in a slightly different way, yet still anachronistically places him in the era of the Inca kings (<i>Sapa</i>) (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('f5b74f18-0bc4-46d2-8a5c-64dd80b74dd1'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman, pp. 87, 123</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('c5bb1db2-0f10-45c5-91ce-52020e770ca9'); return false;\">Poma de Ayala, Felipe Guaman,  pp. 62, 89</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('33cf32da-87cb-414c-a508-daf964dfef15'); return false;\">Gebran, Philomena, pp. 6 - 7</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('922ae4e4-8a1a-40ed-9fa3-ca7d541a05e1'); return false;\">History Tracers</a>).<br /><br />Imagine that you had never encountered any other version beyond Guaman Poma’s account; would you consider it an unquestionable truth?<br /><br />In your opinion, can relying solely on specific sources limit access to other documents and hinder a broader understanding of different worldviews?</div></div></center></p>",
